WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.320 --> 00:00:09.380
SPEAKER: Yeah, welcome.

00:00:09.380 --> 00:00:14.400
We have Sunniva Sorby joining
us today for a talk at Google.

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:15.900
I'll tell you a
little bit about her

00:00:15.900 --> 00:00:18.140
and then we'll get
to her amazing story.

00:00:18.140 --> 00:00:25.380
In 1993, as part of a historic
four-woman expedition,

00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:29.030
Sunniva skied 67 days
across Antarctica

00:00:29.030 --> 00:00:32.299
covering over 700
miles in winds that

00:00:32.299 --> 00:00:38.710
topped 50 miles per hour in
60 degree below zero weather.

00:00:41.570 --> 00:00:46.340
She pulled-- she and the other
women pulled 200-pound sleds,

00:00:46.340 --> 00:00:48.290
and they were actually
the first women's team

00:00:48.290 --> 00:00:51.560
to reach the South Pole in
a human-powered expedition

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:56.410
without the aid of sled
dogs or motorized vehicles.

00:00:56.410 --> 00:00:58.940
Since then, she has
returned to Antarctica

00:00:58.940 --> 00:01:02.920
over 50 times, completed
expeditions on Kilimanjaro

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:04.840
and the Greenland ice sheet.

00:01:04.840 --> 00:01:08.140
She started an adventure
travel company called Red Door

00:01:08.140 --> 00:01:12.250
Adventures to blend her love
of sharing different cultures

00:01:12.250 --> 00:01:16.610
and also to create opportunities
for women in business.

00:01:16.610 --> 00:01:20.590
And through this company,
she's created numerous trips

00:01:20.590 --> 00:01:23.520
to Kilimanjaro and Patagonia.

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:25.500
Currently, she's
the global director

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:29.550
at Polar Latitudes, which
is an expedition cruise

00:01:29.550 --> 00:01:34.510
company that operates two
cruise ships in Antarctica.

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:38.620
And I actually heard
Sunniva's tale firsthand

00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:42.040
at a gathering some
time ago, and I

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:47.190
was truly inspired by
her tale of adversity

00:01:47.190 --> 00:01:51.110
these women overcame,
which included setbacks

00:01:51.110 --> 00:01:54.800
due to gender bias in addition
to the challenging and harsh

00:01:54.800 --> 00:01:56.690
conditions of Antarctica.

00:01:56.690 --> 00:02:00.030
So I'm excited to hear
more about her story today.

00:02:00.030 --> 00:02:01.267
Join us welcoming Sunniva.

00:02:01.267 --> 00:02:02.600
SUNNIVA SORBY: Thank you, James.

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:03.790
Wait, don't leave.

00:02:03.790 --> 00:02:09.080
I, you know, every once in a
while you get to meet somebody

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:11.540
and you know they are salt
of the earth, really nice,

00:02:11.540 --> 00:02:13.647
kind people, and that is you.

00:02:13.647 --> 00:02:15.230
And this is a little
something for you

00:02:15.230 --> 00:02:16.351
and your family to enjoy.

00:02:16.351 --> 00:02:16.850
OK?

00:02:16.850 --> 00:02:17.960
So thanks so much.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:22.220
I really, I really appreciate
all the effort and energy

00:02:22.220 --> 00:02:24.890
that went into me being here.

00:02:24.890 --> 00:02:26.060
I'm Canadian, by the way.

00:02:26.060 --> 00:02:28.650
I live up in Squamish
north of the border.

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:32.510
So if you ever want to come
visit, you're all welcome.

00:02:32.510 --> 00:02:34.520
I'm very, very happy
to be here today.

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:36.690
And can you all hear
me in the back there?

00:02:36.690 --> 00:02:37.190
Yep.

00:02:37.190 --> 00:02:38.600
Good.

00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:40.670
And I just want to
make sure that I

00:02:40.670 --> 00:02:45.710
say hello to all of you that
are listening maybe or watching

00:02:45.710 --> 00:02:47.070
somewhere else.

00:02:47.070 --> 00:02:49.070
It's nice to have
you join me today.

00:02:49.070 --> 00:02:51.980
I'm going to talk
about this expedition

00:02:51.980 --> 00:02:55.370
not because I was part
of it, although I was.

00:02:55.370 --> 00:02:58.250
I'm hoping that
through what I share,

00:02:58.250 --> 00:03:01.070
you will feel like
the human potential

00:03:01.070 --> 00:03:04.850
and the power of our
thoughts over anything

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:10.200
we choose to do in our life is
really the nugget, so to speak.

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:13.010
It's like that great
quote by Henry Ford,

00:03:13.010 --> 00:03:15.560
"Whether you think you can or
you think you can't, you're

00:03:15.560 --> 00:03:16.970
right."

00:03:16.970 --> 00:03:18.050
Right?

00:03:18.050 --> 00:03:21.874
So this expedition took
place in Antarctica.

00:03:21.874 --> 00:03:23.540
And I don't know, has
anyone been there?

00:03:23.540 --> 00:03:24.860
I'm not going to
assume otherwise.

00:03:24.860 --> 00:03:25.359
No.

00:03:25.359 --> 00:03:26.170
OK.

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:29.810
Sometimes a hand goes up in the
audience, so it's, you know,

00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:31.130
it's random.

00:03:31.130 --> 00:03:34.829
Antarctica is an
absolutely amazing place.

00:03:34.829 --> 00:03:36.620
It's the only continent
in the world that's

00:03:36.620 --> 00:03:38.870
not technically owned
by anyone, although it's

00:03:38.870 --> 00:03:40.940
governed by the treaty.

00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:43.880
It is the land of superlatives.

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:46.910
It's called the windiest,
highest, driest, loneliest

00:03:46.910 --> 00:03:48.890
continent on the
face of the Earth,

00:03:48.890 --> 00:03:51.320
and it is so because
it's so far away.

00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:54.335
It takes you-- if you
were to fly from here,

00:03:54.335 --> 00:03:56.690
like Mountain View,
LA, let's say,

00:03:56.690 --> 00:03:59.000
or San Jose is the
closest airport.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.481
You would fly to Buenos
Aires in Argentina,

00:04:02.481 --> 00:04:04.730
and then you would take
another three-hour flight down

00:04:04.730 --> 00:04:08.660
to Ushuaia, and from there
you would get on a ship.

00:04:08.660 --> 00:04:10.629
We run two ships
down in Antarctica.

00:04:10.629 --> 00:04:12.170
And it would take
you almost two days

00:04:12.170 --> 00:04:15.200
to cross this very,
you can see it here,

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:18.170
this narrow body of
water between Argentina

00:04:18.170 --> 00:04:20.240
and the Antarctic Peninsula.

00:04:20.240 --> 00:04:21.959
It's called the Drake Passage.

00:04:21.959 --> 00:04:24.220
And you can see around
Antarctica there

00:04:24.220 --> 00:04:26.420
is nothing to stop the wind.

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:30.140
It's the largest-- all of the
body of waters in the world

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:33.950
circulate around the circumpolar
current in Antarctica.

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:37.550
So it's a very remote
place, and it's

00:04:37.550 --> 00:04:41.900
a place that is not easy to get
to, even by plane or by ship.

00:04:41.900 --> 00:04:47.910
But it's accessible today,
absolutely, with everybody.

00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:51.480
It is a place where unlike-- and
I've never witnessed the Great

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:53.000
Wildebeest Migration,
but I would

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:56.570
imagine that to be an
incredible event, surreal event

00:04:56.570 --> 00:04:59.390
to bear witness to.

00:04:59.390 --> 00:05:01.340
They say that the
Antarctic continent

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:03.110
from one year to
the next doubles

00:05:03.110 --> 00:05:05.690
in size because of the sea ice.

00:05:05.690 --> 00:05:08.090
And we all know that
salt water freezes

00:05:08.090 --> 00:05:11.450
at a temperature lower
than fresh water, yes?

00:05:11.450 --> 00:05:14.360
So when the pack ice
starts to freeze,

00:05:14.360 --> 00:05:16.590
Antarctica doubles in size.

00:05:16.590 --> 00:05:18.980
Now this slide is showing
you how large it is.

00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:22.880
It's, from one tip to the
other side of the continent,

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:25.790
it's 3,400 miles.

00:05:25.790 --> 00:05:27.330
It's huge.

00:05:27.330 --> 00:05:29.330
And even daunting
to think of skiing

00:05:29.330 --> 00:05:30.674
across the Antarctic continent.

00:05:30.674 --> 00:05:32.090
I mean, you can
read about it, you

00:05:32.090 --> 00:05:34.700
can look at beautiful
pictures of the icebergs,

00:05:34.700 --> 00:05:37.490
you can read the stories of
the early polar explorers,

00:05:37.490 --> 00:05:39.920
but until you actually
go to Antarctica

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:42.470
and experience the
absolute beauty

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:45.320
through the light and
the ice and the magnitude

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:47.630
of this place, it
overwhelms you.

00:05:47.630 --> 00:05:48.290
It really does.

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:53.240
So it's fair to say that
when I joined the expedition,

00:05:53.240 --> 00:05:56.540
I read as much as I possibly
could about this place,

00:05:56.540 --> 00:05:59.900
but it didn't prepare
me for the trip itself.

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:03.050
Of course, if we could take that
away from all of experiences,

00:06:03.050 --> 00:06:04.790
none of us would travel, right?

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:06.890
That's the beauty of travel.

00:06:06.890 --> 00:06:08.990
The South Pole is--

00:06:08.990 --> 00:06:10.640
this is 90 degrees
south right here.

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:12.740
It's where the Earth
squeaks on its axis.

00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:14.960
It's where all the lines
of latitude and longitude

00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:16.160
converge.

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:18.350
And it's a surreal thing
to get to the South Pole

00:06:18.350 --> 00:06:22.250
because you feel like, yes, it's
an incredible accomplishment

00:06:22.250 --> 00:06:24.710
to get there, but you see
an actual South Pole Marker.

00:06:24.710 --> 00:06:26.480
So you have to touch it, right?

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:27.370
You have to.

00:06:27.370 --> 00:06:30.080
You don't lick that because
that's not a good thing.

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:33.230
It's like for those of us
who ski, not a good thing.

00:06:33.230 --> 00:06:35.660
But when I got there and
saw the South Pole Marker--

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:37.760
it stands about this high--

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:39.554
there was a row of
South Pole Markers.

00:06:39.554 --> 00:06:40.970
It's a little
defeating, you know,

00:06:40.970 --> 00:06:42.860
to see a whole row of
South Pole Markers.

00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:45.830
And that is because the
ice sheet moves somewhere

00:06:45.830 --> 00:06:49.210
between 3 and 30 feet a year.

00:06:49.210 --> 00:06:50.840
3 and 30 feet a year.

00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:53.050
So if you were to build
a house-- don't do this--

00:06:53.050 --> 00:06:54.716
if you were to build
a house down there,

00:06:54.716 --> 00:06:56.900
it would move every year.

00:06:56.900 --> 00:07:00.040
And eventually, it
would end up down

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:01.630
at the edge of the
Antarctic continent

00:07:01.630 --> 00:07:05.320
where calving occurs,
where the glacier actually

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:06.790
starts to break off.

00:07:06.790 --> 00:07:10.390
And we know that climate change
is a very big deal down there.

00:07:10.390 --> 00:07:12.130
We're bearing witness
to changes in both

00:07:12.130 --> 00:07:13.630
the Arctic and the Antarctic.

00:07:13.630 --> 00:07:15.210
And it's very real down south.

00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:18.250
I see a lot of calving
when I'm driving a Zodiac.

00:07:18.250 --> 00:07:19.390
It's incredible.

00:07:19.390 --> 00:07:23.050
So just to fast forward a little
bit about early exploration

00:07:23.050 --> 00:07:27.400
because you know, 82 years
after the first team of men

00:07:27.400 --> 00:07:30.580
reached the South Pole,
we did our expedition.

00:07:30.580 --> 00:07:32.830
In our life, that's
not a long time really.

00:07:32.830 --> 00:07:35.920
But it's amazing it
took 82 years for women

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:39.340
to even conceive of the idea
of going down to Antarctica.

00:07:39.340 --> 00:07:42.130
And I can tell you that we had
a lot of people look at us.

00:07:42.130 --> 00:07:46.150
I'm the tallest of the four of
us at 5' 6" or whatever I am,

00:07:46.150 --> 00:07:49.690
and the smallest was Anne
Dal Vera, she's 5' 2".

00:07:49.690 --> 00:07:53.120
So this is really a story not
about Sunniva Sorby or Anne Dal

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:55.720
Vera or Ann Bancroft
or Sue Giller.

00:07:55.720 --> 00:07:58.900
This story about the
American Women's Expedition

00:07:58.900 --> 00:08:02.710
is really about the
power of belief.

00:08:02.710 --> 00:08:04.990
Not just individual,
but how important

00:08:04.990 --> 00:08:08.630
it is for us to support each
other in our efforts, you know?

00:08:08.630 --> 00:08:10.480
And the dreams start
when we're small.

00:08:10.480 --> 00:08:15.104
When I was 10 years old, I
dreamt of going to the moon.

00:08:15.104 --> 00:08:17.270
I don't know why, but I
dreamt of going to the moon.

00:08:17.270 --> 00:08:18.130
So what did I do?

00:08:18.130 --> 00:08:21.340
I wrote a letter to NASA, and
I got a nice form letter back

00:08:21.340 --> 00:08:23.300
saying, stay in school.

00:08:23.300 --> 00:08:24.430
So I did.

00:08:24.430 --> 00:08:26.540
And the important
part of that, for me,

00:08:26.540 --> 00:08:28.750
was that my dream
wasn't squashed.

00:08:28.750 --> 00:08:31.600
And I'll tell you that skiing
across the Antarctic continent

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:33.580
and experiencing
the polar ice cap

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:37.522
was very much like what I
imagined the moon to look like.

00:08:37.522 --> 00:08:38.980
So sometimes you
think you're going

00:08:38.980 --> 00:08:41.470
to walk through a red door
and that's that one dream,

00:08:41.470 --> 00:08:43.090
but sometimes it's blue.

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:45.670
So we have to stay awake,
you know, for our ride

00:08:45.670 --> 00:08:49.510
and be open to the very
different ways things

00:08:49.510 --> 00:08:50.830
get presented to us.

00:08:50.830 --> 00:08:53.560
So here we are at the South
Pole, minus 76 degrees,

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:55.660
and we pay tribute
to Amundsen, who

00:08:55.660 --> 00:08:56.950
reached the South Pole first.

00:08:56.950 --> 00:09:00.550
He was a Norwegian, and he was
very efficient in his logistics

00:09:00.550 --> 00:09:03.240
and planning, very
successful with sled dogs.

00:09:03.240 --> 00:09:07.390
Arrived there a full month
before the infamous Robert

00:09:07.390 --> 00:09:08.980
Falcon Scott expedition.

00:09:08.980 --> 00:09:11.230
Has anyone heard
of these stories?

00:09:11.230 --> 00:09:12.160
Yeah?

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:14.680
They're fascinating stories
because not only do they

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:17.920
dig into the human spirit and
what we're capable of doing,

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:20.230
but it's a story
about how, you know,

00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:22.990
Robert Scott, for example,
they get to the South Pole

00:09:22.990 --> 00:09:24.460
and they find a tent.

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:27.220
And then they find a
Norwegian flag waving proudly

00:09:27.220 --> 00:09:28.450
in the wind.

00:09:28.450 --> 00:09:30.640
And there's a letter
inside for Scott.

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:34.700
And then there's also a
letter for the King of Norway.

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:38.110
So it was a bittersweet
thing for Scott's party

00:09:38.110 --> 00:09:40.810
to arrive at the
South Pole defeated.

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:42.670
They didn't get there first.

00:09:42.670 --> 00:09:46.000
And they got there and they
were so badly frostbitten,

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.540
they were very, very
hungry, and they were just,

00:09:49.540 --> 00:09:54.010
quite frankly, their spirits
were completely squashed

00:09:54.010 --> 00:09:56.260
because of Amundsen
getting there before.

00:09:56.260 --> 00:10:02.020
So they made the trek from the
South Pole back to their base,

00:10:02.020 --> 00:10:04.840
past McMurdo where
the Ross Sea is,

00:10:04.840 --> 00:10:06.730
the other side of Antarctica.

00:10:06.730 --> 00:10:08.290
And they never made it.

00:10:08.290 --> 00:10:11.050
It's a very sad story
because the five of them--

00:10:11.050 --> 00:10:13.750
and you can see the sad
looks on their faces here--

00:10:13.750 --> 00:10:17.470
but the five of them didn't
know how close they were

00:10:17.470 --> 00:10:20.560
to a resupply of food and fuel.

00:10:20.560 --> 00:10:22.360
They died at 18 miles.

00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:25.420
And those of you who ride a
bike or we drive a car, 18 miles

00:10:25.420 --> 00:10:26.740
is nothing.

00:10:26.740 --> 00:10:31.210
But in the world of this, 18
miles is an absolute eternity.

00:10:31.210 --> 00:10:34.450
We skied between 10
and 14 miles every day.

00:10:34.450 --> 00:10:35.680
That was our day.

00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:38.230
So 18 miles for them,
they didn't know this,

00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:40.720
they didn't have GPSes, they
didn't use the same equipment

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:42.020
that we have today.

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:44.200
So that was an eternity.

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:46.870
They were in their
tents, and it was

00:10:46.870 --> 00:10:49.480
all they could do actually
to just keep themselves warm.

00:10:49.480 --> 00:10:51.760
And one of the men,
trying to retain

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:55.180
a certain sense of honor,
walks outside the tent,

00:10:55.180 --> 00:10:57.430
and he uses these words--

00:10:57.430 --> 00:11:01.210
I am going outside and
I shall be some time.

00:11:01.210 --> 00:11:02.890
And he walked and
he walked and he

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:05.180
walked, never to be seen again.

00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:08.830
Another one of the party of
five fell into a crevasse,

00:11:08.830 --> 00:11:10.120
and they lost him.

00:11:10.120 --> 00:11:13.059
And the other three were
found frozen in their tents

00:11:13.059 --> 00:11:15.100
the following spring when
a search party came out

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:16.150
to find them.

00:11:16.150 --> 00:11:19.720
And then Scott's last words with
his pen were, for God's sake,

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:21.340
take care of our people.

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:24.460
It's a story-- there's
been hugely debated,

00:11:24.460 --> 00:11:26.530
these particular two
various expeditions.

00:11:26.530 --> 00:11:27.560
They get compared a lot.

00:11:27.560 --> 00:11:29.440
The Norwegians were
far more efficient

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:31.070
than the British team.

00:11:31.070 --> 00:11:33.670
But it's really a story of
what we're capable of doing

00:11:33.670 --> 00:11:38.980
and how planning is absolutely
essential to success, right?

00:11:38.980 --> 00:11:41.200
But nothing-- I mean,
you can plan and prepare

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:42.850
all you want for
a trip like this,

00:11:42.850 --> 00:11:45.740
but then stuff
happens on the inside.

00:11:45.740 --> 00:11:47.260
And we all know
what that's like.

00:11:47.260 --> 00:11:49.600
It's the experience
of it, right?

00:11:49.600 --> 00:11:51.520
So here we are in Punta Arenas.

00:11:51.520 --> 00:11:54.160
We actually flew to
Punta Arenas, Chile.

00:11:54.160 --> 00:11:56.500
And I call this a
bad hair day in Punta

00:11:56.500 --> 00:11:59.410
because our hair is like, woo.

00:11:59.410 --> 00:12:01.320
It's always windy there.

00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:07.300
And we would leave Punta Arenas
and fly eight hours to a place

00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:09.460
at 80 degrees south-- hi--

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:11.650
at 80 degrees south where
there was a base there.

00:12:11.650 --> 00:12:12.820
And that base would--

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:16.240
we with board a Twin Otter and
fly from there to our start

00:12:16.240 --> 00:12:18.220
at the edge of the
Ronne Ice Shelf.

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:21.520
We couldn't leave for two
full weeks from Punta Arenas

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:26.140
because over the Transantarctic
Mountains there was a shadow,

00:12:26.140 --> 00:12:28.870
and the pilot needs to
leave early in the morning

00:12:28.870 --> 00:12:33.190
to be able to avoid the shadow
that this mountain range casts

00:12:33.190 --> 00:12:34.990
on the blue ice runway.

00:12:34.990 --> 00:12:36.490
Two weeks we waited.

00:12:36.490 --> 00:12:38.740
We all know what it's like
to be delayed with a flight

00:12:38.740 --> 00:12:40.156
or something like
that for an hour

00:12:40.156 --> 00:12:41.380
or maybe half a day or a day.

00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:43.570
It's kind of an inconvenience.

00:12:43.570 --> 00:12:46.120
Imagine being delayed two weeks.

00:12:46.120 --> 00:12:48.130
The worst part about
that was the anxiety

00:12:48.130 --> 00:12:49.260
that was building up.

00:12:49.260 --> 00:12:54.655
And it was also bad for
us because you start to--

00:12:54.655 --> 00:12:55.840
we train.

00:12:55.840 --> 00:12:58.150
You know, we're training
really hard for these trips,

00:12:58.150 --> 00:12:59.620
and we're trying to eat
as much as possible.

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:00.911
That was a good thing actually.

00:13:00.911 --> 00:13:03.222
We ate like crazy
for those two weeks.

00:13:03.222 --> 00:13:05.680
And we stayed, you know, tried
to stay in shape by running.

00:13:05.680 --> 00:13:09.010
And we also got to know
some of the other expedition

00:13:09.010 --> 00:13:10.480
members that were down there.

00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:15.340
There was a team from England,
and it was Sir Ranulph Fiennes

00:13:15.340 --> 00:13:16.210
and Mike Stroud.

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:18.520
I don't know if any of you've
heard of that expedition.

00:13:18.520 --> 00:13:23.740
But they were going to
do a study on starvation.

00:13:23.740 --> 00:13:25.600
Doesn't that sound fun?

00:13:25.600 --> 00:13:27.910
They were going to
see how far can we

00:13:27.910 --> 00:13:30.720
go physically,
emotionally, mentally,

00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:33.700
spiritually, how far can
we go before we actually

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:34.960
starve ourselves to death.

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:37.510
They wanted to find out,
you know, that absolute edge

00:13:37.510 --> 00:13:39.910
of what's possible.

00:13:39.910 --> 00:13:40.660
And they did.

00:13:40.660 --> 00:13:44.470
They were actually, they were
taking muscle tissue samples

00:13:44.470 --> 00:13:46.870
from their thighs for
some of the study.

00:13:46.870 --> 00:13:48.447
And they were hailed as heroes.

00:13:48.447 --> 00:13:50.530
They were found-- they
looked more dead than alive

00:13:50.530 --> 00:13:51.571
when they were picked up.

00:13:51.571 --> 00:13:54.820
They were 10 days away
from being very successful.

00:13:54.820 --> 00:13:57.130
But they were on the
cover of "Time" magazine

00:13:57.130 --> 00:14:00.280
when they got back and
hailed as heroes for this.

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:02.500
We, as a group of
four women-- you know,

00:14:02.500 --> 00:14:06.070
women had never tried this
before-- we were extremely

00:14:06.070 --> 00:14:10.090
careful about how we presented
what we were doing to the world

00:14:10.090 --> 00:14:12.790
because we wanted to
go as a team of four

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:14.740
and come back as a team of four.

00:14:14.740 --> 00:14:17.500
We wanted to ski all the way
across the Antarctic continent

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:21.010
from the edge of the Ronne Ice
Shelf, which you see there--

00:14:21.010 --> 00:14:25.150
and we got a nice letter from
Edith Ronne; that ice shelf is

00:14:25.150 --> 00:14:26.530
named after her--

00:14:26.530 --> 00:14:28.720
and we wanted to go
to the South Pole

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:30.220
and then from
there go to McMurdo

00:14:30.220 --> 00:14:33.520
and catch the very last cruise
ship home, which was February

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:35.260
14, Valentine's Day.

00:14:35.260 --> 00:14:37.030
Motivation, you know?

00:14:37.030 --> 00:14:39.430
Everything down there is a
little mathematical equation

00:14:39.430 --> 00:14:42.220
on how many miles you do
every day, how much food you

00:14:42.220 --> 00:14:44.680
bring every day, 2
pounds per person a day.

00:14:44.680 --> 00:14:48.610
6,000 to 7,000 calories
is what we ate a lot.

00:14:48.610 --> 00:14:50.230
And a large
percentage of our diet

00:14:50.230 --> 00:14:52.870
was actually fat
because we need to stay

00:14:52.870 --> 00:14:54.310
insulated from the cold.

00:14:54.310 --> 00:14:56.650
So our goal was
to ski all the way

00:14:56.650 --> 00:14:58.390
across the Antarctic continent.

00:14:58.390 --> 00:15:00.980
I'm not here to talk about that
because that didn't happen.

00:15:00.980 --> 00:15:02.837
We made it to the South Pole.

00:15:02.837 --> 00:15:05.170
The reason for that is losing
two weeks in the beginning

00:15:05.170 --> 00:15:10.030
to bad weather, and also,
I got very, very sick.

00:15:10.030 --> 00:15:13.060
I had bronchitis
for over 45 days.

00:15:13.060 --> 00:15:15.550
I had tendinitis in both feet.

00:15:15.550 --> 00:15:18.790
And I mean, I look
back on this trip

00:15:18.790 --> 00:15:21.430
and sometimes I'm not sure
how in the world I did it.

00:15:21.430 --> 00:15:24.370
I clearly was not alone,
if you know what I mean.

00:15:24.370 --> 00:15:26.011
So our mantra was,
four to the pole.

00:15:26.011 --> 00:15:28.510
When all these setbacks and all
these things were happening,

00:15:28.510 --> 00:15:31.150
it was, no, not two people
will go to the South Pole

00:15:31.150 --> 00:15:32.980
and call that a success.

00:15:32.980 --> 00:15:34.780
It will be the four of us.

00:15:34.780 --> 00:15:37.810
Our goal was to also
pull all of our weight.

00:15:37.810 --> 00:15:41.560
We had 200 pounds in a sled
that was about 6 feet long.

00:15:41.560 --> 00:15:44.830
And you look at me and we can
look at anybody and go, what?

00:15:44.830 --> 00:15:46.150
You've pulled a 200-pound sled?

00:15:46.150 --> 00:15:47.470
Or, you've skied down Mt.

00:15:47.470 --> 00:15:48.640
Rainier?

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:50.110
You know?

00:15:50.110 --> 00:15:51.250
We're amazing people.

00:15:51.250 --> 00:15:53.890
We are amazing when we
put our minds to it.

00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:56.290
I'm not sure how
we did this uphill.

00:15:56.290 --> 00:15:59.170
We start at 3,000 feet and
we ski up to the South Pole,

00:15:59.170 --> 00:16:01.450
which is 9,300 feet.

00:16:01.450 --> 00:16:03.780
I can tell you that
momentum is everything.

00:16:03.780 --> 00:16:05.020
Do you know what I mean?

00:16:05.020 --> 00:16:06.730
You don't stop, you go.

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:07.570
You do a little--

00:16:07.570 --> 00:16:10.930
one breath, one pole
plant, one tug of the sled,

00:16:10.930 --> 00:16:13.270
and then you've got the next
step, and you just repeat.

00:16:13.270 --> 00:16:15.820
You press repeat,
repeat, repeat.

00:16:15.820 --> 00:16:18.250
It's not like eating the big
steak at once or something.

00:16:18.250 --> 00:16:19.840
It's taking small bites.

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:23.410
So you see heel
lifters on our skis.

00:16:23.410 --> 00:16:24.610
That was really important.

00:16:24.610 --> 00:16:26.410
So we were elevated
and we were always

00:16:26.410 --> 00:16:27.880
move-- we were
always like, leaning

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:29.463
at a little bit of
an angle like that.

00:16:29.463 --> 00:16:32.262
So we could actually
pull the sled.

00:16:32.262 --> 00:16:33.220
It was very, very hard.

00:16:33.220 --> 00:16:36.460
And in there was everything
we needed, from food

00:16:36.460 --> 00:16:39.730
and white gas, fuel to cook.

00:16:39.730 --> 00:16:41.360
2 pounds per person per day.

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:44.200
You look at one of those
bags and it was 32 pounds.

00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:48.890
So it would be, it would
be, excuse me, yeah,

00:16:48.890 --> 00:16:50.630
it would be 32
pounds in one bag.

00:16:50.630 --> 00:16:52.310
That's for two women
for eight days.

00:16:52.310 --> 00:16:55.770
And every eight days, we
rotated a new tent partner.

00:16:55.770 --> 00:16:58.120
Do you think that's
kind of important?

00:16:58.120 --> 00:17:00.550
Super important because
after eight days and you're

00:17:00.550 --> 00:17:03.700
in a tent with someone, you
know everything about them.

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:05.219
You know way too
much about them.

00:17:05.219 --> 00:17:06.760
And you need a little
bit of a break.

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:10.771
So it was a strategic
decision on our part.

00:17:10.771 --> 00:17:11.770
So we've got everything.

00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:15.010
We've got-- all the
food gets prepackaged.

00:17:15.010 --> 00:17:18.391
We had kids, we had so many
children follow our project,

00:17:18.391 --> 00:17:20.349
and they signed little
notes, and they put them

00:17:20.349 --> 00:17:21.970
in the food bag.

00:17:21.970 --> 00:17:24.609
So we never know what message we
were getting when we opened up

00:17:24.609 --> 00:17:26.800
a new bag, and just
the different ways

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:28.420
that support came to us.

00:17:28.420 --> 00:17:30.490
Our project cost
a million dollars,

00:17:30.490 --> 00:17:32.440
which today is nothing.

00:17:32.440 --> 00:17:33.460
Well, maybe it is.

00:17:33.460 --> 00:17:35.360
It is, actually.

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:37.840
But we didn't have
one corporate sponsor

00:17:37.840 --> 00:17:40.780
that signed on board to
our expedition, not one.

00:17:40.780 --> 00:17:44.590
I gave a presentation last
week and a guy said, you know,

00:17:44.590 --> 00:17:47.170
if you did this, if you
did this expedition today,

00:17:47.170 --> 00:17:49.360
you would all be millionaires.

00:17:49.360 --> 00:17:52.431
And I'm not a millionaire,
but I do feel very rich inside

00:17:52.431 --> 00:17:53.430
if you know what I mean.

00:17:53.430 --> 00:17:55.180
And I think that
counts for a lot.

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:59.077
So a million dollar expedition,
not one corporate sponsor

00:17:59.077 --> 00:17:59.660
came on board.

00:17:59.660 --> 00:18:02.320
We had Nike and L'Oreal
that were thinking about it,

00:18:02.320 --> 00:18:03.610
but they didn't join.

00:18:03.610 --> 00:18:07.300
So we raised money from
people like yourselves.

00:18:07.300 --> 00:18:09.982
The average donation was $25.

00:18:09.982 --> 00:18:11.440
We had money-- we
had a dollar that

00:18:11.440 --> 00:18:13.648
was sent all the way from
Germany to the headquarters

00:18:13.648 --> 00:18:15.340
in Minnesota with
a note saying, this

00:18:15.340 --> 00:18:17.350
is the only American
money I have.

00:18:17.350 --> 00:18:18.200
But-- you know?

00:18:18.200 --> 00:18:21.010
But it was like, that
was so meaningful for us.

00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:24.010
So we raised $600,000 like that.

00:18:24.010 --> 00:18:28.090
Selling T-shirts, you
know, selling our souls,

00:18:28.090 --> 00:18:30.040
traveling around
doing presentations.

00:18:30.040 --> 00:18:33.040
And the extra $400,000 we
raised when we got back.

00:18:33.040 --> 00:18:35.410
And it took us five years
to raise that extra $400,000

00:18:35.410 --> 00:18:36.530
when we got back.

00:18:36.530 --> 00:18:40.060
So it's an incredible story
of just the power of people,

00:18:40.060 --> 00:18:41.140
you know?

00:18:41.140 --> 00:18:42.550
And you're, at
Google, you're all

00:18:42.550 --> 00:18:45.260
about connecting things and
people and the community,

00:18:45.260 --> 00:18:47.110
and I love what you
have going on here.

00:18:47.110 --> 00:18:49.270
It's absolutely incredible.

00:18:49.270 --> 00:18:51.610
And I think that
cohesiveness and, you know,

00:18:51.610 --> 00:18:54.190
being connected with
one another is so key.

00:18:54.190 --> 00:18:58.630
And for us, it really was
the fuel for our expedition.

00:18:58.630 --> 00:19:00.490
On one day-- and you
know, as four women,

00:19:00.490 --> 00:19:02.620
we all had our
cycles down there.

00:19:02.620 --> 00:19:06.310
And on-- actually,
after one month we

00:19:06.310 --> 00:19:07.520
were all timed together.

00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:09.970
That's kind of scary, four
women who were on their cycles

00:19:09.970 --> 00:19:10.678
at the same time.

00:19:10.678 --> 00:19:12.630
We were like cats, you know?

00:19:12.630 --> 00:19:14.960
It kind of-- it was
pretty interesting.

00:19:14.960 --> 00:19:18.220
But Ann Bancroft, who I was
tenting with at the time,

00:19:18.220 --> 00:19:19.550
wasn't feeling very well.

00:19:19.550 --> 00:19:22.630
And after a day of the
sled and the harness

00:19:22.630 --> 00:19:26.107
tugging at her stomach, it
was really, really hard.

00:19:26.107 --> 00:19:27.940
So I said, I'm going
to make dinner tonight.

00:19:27.940 --> 00:19:30.880
And we did rotate who would
cook breakfast and dinner.

00:19:30.880 --> 00:19:33.470
And I made her a meal and
it was macaroni and cheese.

00:19:33.470 --> 00:19:35.590
I mean, who goes wrong
with mac and cheese, right?

00:19:35.590 --> 00:19:36.530
So simple.

00:19:36.530 --> 00:19:37.690
You've got the-- we know.

00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:41.170
It's like butter, the noodles,
cheese powder, and some milk,

00:19:41.170 --> 00:19:41.710
right?

00:19:41.710 --> 00:19:42.751
Do you do it differently?

00:19:42.751 --> 00:19:44.110
No, it's so easy.

00:19:44.110 --> 00:19:47.830
So I grab-- I wasn't part of
the, you know, all of the bags

00:19:47.830 --> 00:19:52.900
that we had to put into
various 32-pound stuff sacks.

00:19:52.900 --> 00:19:55.930
So I grabbed what I thought
was the cheese powder

00:19:55.930 --> 00:19:58.510
and I mixed it in with the
macaroni and the butter,

00:19:58.510 --> 00:20:00.110
lots of butter, lots of butter.

00:20:00.110 --> 00:20:03.640
And Ann takes a bite of this and
kind of whips her head around

00:20:03.640 --> 00:20:07.104
and looks at me and she goes,
what did you put in here?

00:20:07.104 --> 00:20:08.770
And I'm looking at
her and I take a bite

00:20:08.770 --> 00:20:11.510
and I thought, wow,
this is really awful.

00:20:11.510 --> 00:20:12.640
This was awful.

00:20:12.640 --> 00:20:14.260
And I realized that
I mixed, instead

00:20:14.260 --> 00:20:17.110
of cheese powder, orange
drink with the macaroni

00:20:17.110 --> 00:20:18.110
and the butter.

00:20:18.110 --> 00:20:19.310
Don't do that at home, OK?

00:20:19.310 --> 00:20:20.470
It was so awful.

00:20:20.470 --> 00:20:22.240
And the worst part
for us is we had

00:20:22.240 --> 00:20:24.280
to eat every single
bit of it because that

00:20:24.280 --> 00:20:26.710
was our ration for the night.

00:20:26.710 --> 00:20:29.440
So you've got to be very
careful who you're tenting with

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:32.150
and who's cooking, number one.

00:20:32.150 --> 00:20:33.670
Another goal that
we had in addition

00:20:33.670 --> 00:20:36.430
to pulling our own weight
was to communicate with kids.

00:20:36.430 --> 00:20:39.730
And it's not done the
same way today, of course.

00:20:39.730 --> 00:20:41.950
We had a 30-pound
military radio that we

00:20:41.950 --> 00:20:43.630
used on this expedition.

00:20:43.630 --> 00:20:44.550
That's heavy.

00:20:44.550 --> 00:20:46.330
30-pound military radio.

00:20:46.330 --> 00:20:49.240
We set up skis and ski
poles and hung a dipole

00:20:49.240 --> 00:20:51.355
across the skis
and the poles so we

00:20:51.355 --> 00:20:53.230
could communicate in
the direction of Patriot

00:20:53.230 --> 00:20:54.750
Hills, which was--

00:20:54.750 --> 00:20:56.650
there's a base
there still today.

00:20:56.650 --> 00:20:58.450
If you wanted to go
down to Antarctica

00:20:58.450 --> 00:21:01.060
and photograph the emperor
penguins or climb Mt.

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:05.020
Vinson or ski to the South Pole,
you would go to Patriot Hills.

00:21:05.020 --> 00:21:06.610
It's 80 degrees south.

00:21:06.610 --> 00:21:08.770
And that's where we were
communicating every three

00:21:08.770 --> 00:21:09.970
nights at 7 o'clock.

00:21:09.970 --> 00:21:10.990
That was our sched time.

00:21:10.990 --> 00:21:12.520
Our call sign was AWE--

00:21:12.520 --> 00:21:15.160
alpha whiskey echo,
alpha whiskey echo.

00:21:15.160 --> 00:21:16.690
So we would call
into Patriot Hills

00:21:16.690 --> 00:21:19.240
and we would let them know
where we were, how we were,

00:21:19.240 --> 00:21:21.070
how our food was,
how our fuel was,

00:21:21.070 --> 00:21:22.665
and anything else to report out.

00:21:22.665 --> 00:21:24.330
It was all one way.

00:21:24.330 --> 00:21:27.670
Well, two way with them,
but pretty much one way.

00:21:27.670 --> 00:21:30.100
We had no communication
with the outside world.

00:21:30.100 --> 00:21:33.460
Doesn't that seem
absolutely foreign today?

00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:35.170
I mean, on a trip
today we would be

00:21:35.170 --> 00:21:38.380
able to take like a handheld
iridium satellite phone.

00:21:38.380 --> 00:21:40.210
We wouldn't-- and we could talk.

00:21:40.210 --> 00:21:43.060
We could say we could, we
could order pizza if we wanted

00:21:43.060 --> 00:21:46.161
to-- which I tried on Greenland,
but they didn't deliver

00:21:46.161 --> 00:21:46.660
Domino's.

00:21:46.660 --> 00:21:48.410
Say they deliver
anywhere, but they don't.

00:21:50.416 --> 00:21:51.790
I did that, and
I went and talked

00:21:51.790 --> 00:21:53.730
to the manager when I
came back to San Diego.

00:21:53.730 --> 00:21:54.970
But it's kind of funny.

00:21:54.970 --> 00:21:57.310
So communication for us
to the outside world,

00:21:57.310 --> 00:22:00.040
we had 100,000 kids
followed us with a map

00:22:00.040 --> 00:22:03.720
that National Geographic
donated, and pushpins on a map.

00:22:03.720 --> 00:22:05.200
There was no internet.

00:22:05.200 --> 00:22:07.510
This is 1992, '93.

00:22:07.510 --> 00:22:11.050
And I still, I mean, I really
do enjoy sharing this story

00:22:11.050 --> 00:22:14.432
because it's about the absolute
simplicity around how we

00:22:14.432 --> 00:22:15.640
can move around in the world.

00:22:15.640 --> 00:22:19.750
This expedition was maybe
too far ahead of its time,

00:22:19.750 --> 00:22:20.750
if you know what I mean.

00:22:20.750 --> 00:22:22.750
Maybe-- we were the first
to do it and the first

00:22:22.750 --> 00:22:24.970
to succeed arriving
at the South Pole,

00:22:24.970 --> 00:22:28.000
but I wonder in retrospect,
with the internet, what that

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:29.170
would have done to our trip.

00:22:29.170 --> 00:22:31.330
We had no way of
knowing how people were.

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:34.450
And that was actually
sometimes disconcerting.

00:22:34.450 --> 00:22:37.660
We were also doing research
on our physical bodies

00:22:37.660 --> 00:22:39.970
because we had four very
different body types,

00:22:39.970 --> 00:22:41.950
and you know, how
far, how long does it

00:22:41.950 --> 00:22:44.320
take for you to get really
cold and start shivering.

00:22:44.320 --> 00:22:46.210
Shivering is a really
good thing, actually.

00:22:46.210 --> 00:22:47.980
It's our normal
response to the cold.

00:22:47.980 --> 00:22:49.896
But when you stop
shivering, that's dangerous.

00:22:49.896 --> 00:22:52.510
So when you get to that
point, you know, you

00:22:52.510 --> 00:22:54.400
start to become hypothermic.

00:22:54.400 --> 00:22:56.330
Very, very dangerous
place to be.

00:22:56.330 --> 00:22:58.360
So we-- somebody's
idea of a joke

00:22:58.360 --> 00:23:01.390
was to put a beach
chair in an ice chamber,

00:23:01.390 --> 00:23:05.530
like a room, that was 5
degrees, and electrodes

00:23:05.530 --> 00:23:08.020
all over our body to measure
our body temperature.

00:23:08.020 --> 00:23:09.820
And we'd had to try to--

00:23:09.820 --> 00:23:10.540
dexterity.

00:23:10.540 --> 00:23:12.430
You just stop
functioning in the cold.

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:13.472
You all know that, right?

00:23:13.472 --> 00:23:15.055
Although you live
in a beautiful place

00:23:15.055 --> 00:23:16.570
and it's warm all
the time, I know

00:23:16.570 --> 00:23:18.670
you are out there doing
things in the cold, too.

00:23:18.670 --> 00:23:21.460
So just knowing all
of this beforehand

00:23:21.460 --> 00:23:23.770
is very helpful for us
in terms of food planning

00:23:23.770 --> 00:23:25.145
and what kind of
gear we're going

00:23:25.145 --> 00:23:26.800
to use on a trip like this.

00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:31.090
So I'm sharing this,
which is coined by a man

00:23:31.090 --> 00:23:32.590
by the name of Paul Petzoldt.

00:23:32.590 --> 00:23:34.990
He's the founder of NOLS, the
National Outdoor Leadership

00:23:34.990 --> 00:23:35.960
School.

00:23:35.960 --> 00:23:39.400
And he's coined-- he came up
with this expedition behavior.

00:23:39.400 --> 00:23:42.040
And I like this because
it's the kind of way

00:23:42.040 --> 00:23:45.130
of thinking that makes
sure that you absolutely

00:23:45.130 --> 00:23:47.620
take responsibility
and care of yourself,

00:23:47.620 --> 00:23:51.940
but then in doing that, you are
then able to have the group's

00:23:51.940 --> 00:23:52.835
care in mind.

00:23:52.835 --> 00:23:53.710
You know what I mean?

00:23:53.710 --> 00:23:55.240
So it's all about
the collective.

00:23:55.240 --> 00:23:57.040
I think if every
company operated

00:23:57.040 --> 00:24:00.085
with expedition behavior,
wouldn't we be all better off?

00:24:00.085 --> 00:24:03.190
I'm sure you do it here, but
this was an important thing

00:24:03.190 --> 00:24:06.550
for us on the expedition
to have or to adopt

00:24:06.550 --> 00:24:08.920
as sort of how we
treat one another,

00:24:08.920 --> 00:24:11.260
although it didn't
always happen.

00:24:11.260 --> 00:24:13.300
I am going to
share a video clip,

00:24:13.300 --> 00:24:16.780
and this clip is just me joining
the expedition because that's

00:24:16.780 --> 00:24:17.650
a story in itself.

00:24:17.650 --> 00:24:19.810
I had six months to prepare
for this expedition,

00:24:19.810 --> 00:24:21.760
unlike the others where
they had two or three

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:23.410
years, or four years.

00:24:23.410 --> 00:24:26.230
So a little-- we'll roll
the video clip on this.

00:24:26.230 --> 00:24:26.730
Thanks.

00:24:32.504 --> 00:24:33.170
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

